{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"66e7baa5-6835-401c-afbc-2e206d3e6df7","content":"\n\nThe .NET Android build system on macOS **doesn't reliably use `JAVA_HOME`**. It has its own JDK search logic and looks in specific paths — Adoptium Temurin installs to a location it doesn't check by default.\n\n**Two fixes (pick one):**\n\n**Option A — Install Microsoft's OpenJDK 17 (recommended):**\n```bash\ndotnet workload install maui   # bundles Microsoft OpenJDK 17\n```\nThis places the JDK where the build system expects it.\n\n**Option B — Point the build at your Temurin JDK explicitly:**\n\nAdd this to your `.csproj` (inside a `<PropertyGroup>`):\n```xml\n<JavaSdkDirectory>/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home</JavaSdkDirectory>\n```\n\nOr pass it on the command line:\n```bash\ndotnet build -p:JavaSdkDirectory=/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home\n```\n\n> Verify your exact path with:  \n> `/usr/libexec/java_home -v 17`\n\nOption A is the path of least resistance — the MAUI workload bundles a JDK that \"just works.\"","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4414d900-2fe8-4b5d-b6ae-d18ecb2a21f5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI Android build failure related to Java. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed. Let me think about what the common issue is here.\n\nThe common issue with .NET MAUI Android builds and Java is that .NET MAUI / Android SDK requires a specific JDK version. Starting with .NET 8, the Android SDK requires JDK 17. But there's a well-known issue: .NET MAUI on macOS often looks for the JDK in a specific location, or the Microsoft OpenJDK is expected.\n\nActually, the most common issue is that **.NET 8+ Android builds require JDK 17**, but more specifically, there's a known problem where the build process doesn't respect `JAVA_HOME` and instead looks for the Microsoft OpenJDK distribution installed via the Android workload.\n\n\nThe build system has its own JDK detection logic that may not properly recognize the Temurin installation, even with JAVA_HOME set. The error could stem from version detection issues, the build looking in unexpected locations, or incompatibility between how Temurin is installed and what the Android build toolchain expects. expects the Microsoft OpenJDK.\n\nBut actually, I think the most well-known issue is simpler: **.NET 9 requires JDK 17**, and .NET 8 also requires JDK 17. If they have JDK 17, it should work... unless the issue is that the build is picking up a different JDK.\n\nHmm, let me reconsider. On macOS specifically, there's a common issue where:\n\n1. The `JAVA_HOME` environment variable might not be picked up by the IDE (Visual Studio for Mac, or VS Code)\n2. The .NET Android SDK has a specific search order for JDK\n\nThe real culprit is usually that on macOS, the .NET Android build system looks for JDK in specific hardcoded paths, and Adoptium Temurin doesn't always get detected properly. The Microsoft OpenJDK 17 is the recommended solution since it's installed as part of the Android workload and integrates seamlessly with the build system. The quickest fix is typically to either install Microsoft's OpenJDK 17 through the workload, explicitly set `<JavaSdkDirectory>` in the project file, or ensure `JAVA_HOME` is properly configured. The .NET Android SDK doesn't automatically detect third-party JDKs like Temurin on macOS, so the most reliable fix is to either install Microsoft's OpenJDK 17 through the dotnet workload (which bundles everything) or explicitly configure the `JavaSdkDirectory` property in the project file.","outputTokens":1433},"id":"147a9197-284e-476d-a18b-0e53e01ec472","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:44:14.855Z","parentId":"5fea8677-0776-4609-bf1b-314b8281788f"}
